<p><em>Scott in Wanganui </em></p>
<p><em>The fine weather inspired me to try something a bit different with our team today as we continued our weekly &quot;ritual&quot; of praying for the other YFC mission bases. We found it worthwhile, and thought others might benefit from giving it a go as well.</em></p>
<p><em>I printed a copy of the prayer list for everyone, and we went for a prayer walk. </em></p>
<p><em>We didn't know where we were going (symbolic of our change process as well!), and struggled at times to &quot;keep in step&quot; with each other, faced various distractions, and sometimes couldn't hear each other praying for all the noisy trucks, etc. that passed by. But still, we took turns, praying aloud as we walked. </em></p>
<p><em>When we finished, various team members noted the following:</em></p>
<ol>
  <li><em>The walk was symbolic of how we ought to be journeying together. Forward motion, allowing God to guide, etc.</em></li>
  <li><em> Learning to pray with distractions is probably a more valuable discipline than always trying to pray in an artificial environment without distractions. </em></li>
  <li><em> Being in the community was a reminder that we are (or ought to be) missional, not only on club night, but also as we pray. </em></li>
  <li><em> Not being able to hear one another was a reminder that the words we're praying are for God, not a human audience. </em></li>
  <li><em> Praying &quot;on the go&quot; is a reminder that prayer shouldn't be something we just do at designated times or in designated places, but always and everywhere. </em></li>
</ol>
